This species is interesting chiefly because almost every part of the plant is preserved. Unfortunately, however, the spores are missing. In regard to the parts preserved the species does not show any characteristics that could prevent it from being ranged under the genus Equisetum.

In some species of Equisetites, Prof. HALLE has been able to find spores, which are different from those of the existing species of Equisetum (HALLE 1908). Maceration experiments were made on sporophyll-fragments of the present species; but, as has already been mentioned, the result was negative. Some stem-fragments were also treated in the same way. When the fragments had been for about a fortnight in the maceration solution, it was possible to observa that the stem was provided with stomata, which were situated in regular longitudinal rows on the internodes. Their shape seemed to be the same as that of the recent Equisetaceae. A cuticular structure was plainly visible, consisting partly of thin longi- tudinal lists with very short, rib-like protuberances lying close together and standing out at right angles, partly of shorter transversal dotted lines. When ammonia was added, the whole preparation gradually dissolved, so that no draw- ings could be made.
